1 retention of biological evidence in felony cases for a
2 certain period under specified circumstances.
3 SECTION 2. Section 844D-1, Hawaii Revised Statutes, is
4 amended by adding a new definition to be appropriately inserted
5 and to read as follows:
6 ""Contested issue in the case" means, as reflected in the
7 record, the defendant affirmatively disputed being the
8 perpetrator of the charged offense by raising or relying on
9 misidentification, alibi, mistaken identity, third-party
10 perpetrator, or similar theory, or by otherwise placing the
11 perpetrator's identity in issue through motion, argument, cross-
12 examination, evidence, or proffer."
13 SECTION 3. Section 844D-121, Hawaii Revised Statutes, is
14 amended to read as follows:
15 "S844D-121 Petition fox post-conviction DNA testing.
16 Notwithstanding any other law or rule of court governing post­
17 conviction relief to the contrary, a person who was convicted of
18 and sentenced for a crime, or acquitted of a crime on the ground
19 of physical or mental disease, disorder, or defect excluding
20 responsibility, may file a motion, at any time, for DNA analysis
21 of any evidence that:
